BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) â€” Within hours of the FIFA scandal breaking, Sergio Jadue, the president of Chileâ€™s soccer federation, was declaring his innocence even though he wasnâ€™t formally accused of anything. Jadue was referring to a part of Wednesdayâ€™s sweeping U.S. Justice Department indictments that, without specifying them by name, said the 10 presidents of the South American Football Confederation were to receive bribes from a company called Datisa in exchange for transmission rights to games of the Copa America, the tournament of the continentâ€™s national teams. Jadue said $1.5 million was indeed transferred in late 2013 from the confederation, known as CONMEBOL, but it was an advance on a contract for Copa America. â€œI donâ€™t even have to be worried,â€ Jadue told La Tercera newspaper from Switzerland, where he attended a FIFA meeting. â€œThis wonâ€™t affect at all the work of the federation or its president.â€ Itâ€™s hard to imagine that anything will be business as usual when it comes to soccer here. The FIFA investigations are having a ripple effect across soccer-crazy South America, whose teams have won nine World Cups and where national squads are preparing for the continental tournament that starts in two weeks. Governments of powerhouses Argentina and Brazil, which for years looked the other way amid rumblings of corruption at various levels of the â€œbeautiful game,â€ are launching investigations. And powerbrokers such as Paraguayan Nicolas Leoz, former president of CONMEBOL, are on the defensive. The 86-year-old defiantly declared his innocence from a hospital as Paraguay processes a U.S. extradition request. â€œWe are looking at a game that has been mismanaged for so long, and so many were implicit,â€ said Christopher Gaffney, author of â€œTemples of the Earthbound Gods,â€ a look at the history of soccer in Argentina and Brazil. â€œOnce you start pulling on the strings, the whole thing could start to unravel.â€ In Argentina, prosecutors have charged three men implicated in the scandal with tax fraud, racketeering and money laundering for their involvement. The Federal Administration for Public Revenue charged Alejandro Burzaco, president of the sports marketing company Torneos y Competencias, and Mariano and Hugo Jinkis, owners of the sports media business Full Play. All were named Wednesday in a U.S. indictment saying they bribed soccer officials in exchange for the rights to international tournaments. The United States has requested their extradition. Both Jinkins were in Argentina, their lawyer Jorge Anzorreguy said, but had not turned themselves in. Burzacoâ€™s whereabouts were unknown. Cabinet chief Anibal Fernandez said authorities would look closely at the companies to see if tax evasion went beyond the three men. The scandal has quickly changed things in Argentine soccer. Before his death last year, Julio Grondona was seen as the right hand of FIFA president Joseph Blatter and head of the national football association. Called the â€œmonje negro,â€ or â€œblack monk,â€ because of his reputation of making FIFA decisions behind the scenes, Grondona would surely have been under the microscope of U.S. prosecutors. On Friday, Argentina voted against Blatter, who was re-elected easily. â€œBeyond the initial commotion, every time you open a can of worms it means something positive for the future,â€ said Mariano Berges, a former judge who helped form the Buenos Aires-based group â€œLetâ€™s Save Football.â€ Berges said that it would have been nearly impossible for such an investigation to begin in Argentina, where similar to many countries in the region, top politicians and businessmen are heavily involved in the sport. â€œComing from the United States, itâ€™s more acceptable,â€ said Berges. In Brazil, Justice Minister Jose Eduardo Cardozo said authorities were studying the indictments to see where or how Brazilian businessmen and soccer executives might have committed crimes. Rio de Janeiro-based Klefer Sports Marketing company had to turn over documents related to its contract with the Brazilian soccer confederation for marketing rights to the domestic soccer championship. Klefer signed the contract together with Traffic, a Brazilian sports marketing company that American officials are investigating. Klefer has denied any wrongdoing. In Rio de Janeiro, the Brazilian confederation ordered the removal of the name of Jose Maria Marin from its lavish building. The 83-year-old Marin was one of 14 senior sports officials and marketing executives charged in the FIFA investigation. He was arrested in Zurich. On Thursday, the Brazilian Senate approved the request made by former soccer star and now Senator Romario for a congressional panel to investigate corruption in soccer. In Uruguay, newspapers were filled with accounts claiming corrupt dealings by former CONMEBOL president Eugenio Figueredo. He was already being investigated in Uruguay for irregularities during his long tenure as CONMEBOL vice president. In a continent where many are often skeptical of U.S. involvement in local affairs, governments appeared eager to work with American investigators. Although no Colombian national was named in the indictments, the countryâ€™s attorney general said investigators would review the international financial transactions of top soccer officials. An original character, or something else. If you would I would like to submit evidence that Kat is in fact, Maryâ€™s sister.ï¿½ï¿½ These are both official images from both games, obvious physical differences aside we never know too much about Kat, other than she has is a medium, she can go in between Limbo and the physical world. (Reference!)ï¿½ï¿½ Kat and Mary are both sisters, with Mary being the oldest. She seeâ€™s her father kill their mother and runs taking Kat with her, leaving her in the care of someone in the city. Kat runs even farther and Mary canâ€™t find her, and assumes sheâ€™s dead. Kat learns about strange things in her hometown and thinks Mary is dead. Weir 5 is at the foot of the bank behind Rodman Hall and the Walker Botanical Garden. Ontario Power Generation (OPG) owns the creek bed and controls water flow in that area of the Twelve. preprotext: Music Distribution In China.. A new report by Mathew D ofï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½The Global Outpost this week provides a great summary of the current state of music distribution in China. Navigating the Chinese music market can be a minefield for those that donâ€™t have the experience or connections in place and this piece sums it up as well as bringing some solid insight from someone directly on the ground in the PRC. To break it down there are a few components that we noted from the article that we wanted to share with our readers. 1. Distributing Music in Chinaï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ While a huge potential market in terms of numbers, the actual number of outlets to release music are mostly limited to the major web giants and telcos, something we have outlined in an earlier post at Rightsify. This has both pros and cons, while these companies do have the capital, resources, and user-base to get your music out there, the Western model and distribution infrastructure just isnâ€™t there, yet. As noted in the report Even after a deal has been struck and with the distributor/ label ready to deliver content directly to these services, many of these services continue to maintain their content farms as their main source of audio files and metadata. Most Chinese music services are unable to process XML or DDEX formats for ingestion, making it harder for international distributors to tap into these music services directly This is more of a case of the market needing to adopt to international standards and as these services continue to license more foreign content they will most likely become more integrated with international distributors.ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ 2. Accessing Music As withï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½most countries in the Asia-Pacific region, mobile is the name of the game and when it comes to accessing music, itâ€™s no different.ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ Major state-owned telcos such as China Mobile, China Telecom and China Unicom all have their own streaming services which are likely to be bundled into devices and the major web giants tend to use music as part of their broader network of products and services, whether it be mobile messaging, video or even hardware.ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ 3. Music Rights In terms of music rights in China, the copyright system is still in itâ€™s early stages and from what we gather the recording side is much more established than publishing. It is also important to note that some of the major publishers and other sizeable independent publishers have not assigned their digital rights to the collection society, Music Copyright Society of China (MCSC) and instead have engaged independent distributors to this task. Whilst the MCSC is already covering a lot of ground, the content of many other publishers needs to be policed, which they assign to individual distributors in China to negotiate and deal directly with the music services to license accordingly From a Western standpoint, the idea of assigning your collection rights to an independent third-party instead of an ASCAP, PRS or GEMA type organization sounds bizarre and maybe even radical but in the Chinese market it seems that this might be delivering better results and ultimately more revenue for rights holders. 4. Royalties and Reporting Expectedly, the royalty and reporting infrastructure still has a way to go before reaching international standards. Royalty reporting, or the lack of it, is one of the biggest areas holding back the long-term development of a healthier music industry ecosystem in China. Currently, Chinaâ€™s music services do not provide royalty reports or have systems that properly track music consumption by users. Over time the reporting factor is likely to evolve and adopt as the platforms and services that are acquiring music will become more dependent on music as an exclusivity tool that helps drive traffic and sales to other apps or services.ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ The analytics and data from music consumption is also lacking quite badly. While, YouKu, Baidu, and Tencent do have APIâ€™s, many of them are in Chinese only so there is limited data on what music is being consumed from which provinces, cities as well as the demographics of the listeners. So while the Chinese music market does seem to be theï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½â€˜Wild Wild Eastâ€™, it no doubt has major long-term potential for rights holders and should not be ignored.ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ You can read the full report on The State of Music Distribution In China here.

Navy divers to help raise confederate warship artifacts. NORFOLK, Va. (AP) â€” The Navy is preparing to send one if its premier diving teams to Georgia to help salvage a Confederate warship from the depths of the Savannah River. Before it ever fired a shot, the 1,200 ton ironclad CSS Georgia was scuttled by its own crew to prevent its capture by Gen. William T. Sherman when his Union army took Savannah in December 1864. Today, itâ€™s considered a captured enemy vessel and is property of the U.S. Navy. The shipwreck is being removed as part of a $703 million project to deepen the river channel so larger cargo ships can reach the Port of Savannah. Before the harbor can be deepened, the CSS Georgia has to be raised. After years of planning, archaeologists began tagging and recording the locations of thousands of pieces from the shipwreck in January. Theyâ€™ve been able to bring smaller artifacts to the surface, but the Navy is being called in to raise the 120-foot-long shipâ€™s larger sections and weapons. Navy divers are scheduled to arrive at the site near downtown Savannah about 100 yards from the shore on June 1. The Navy divers assigned to the project are from the same unit thatâ€™s had some of the militaryâ€™s highest profile salvage operations. That includes the Civil War ironclad USS Monitor, TWA Flight 800, Swiss Air Flight 111, as well as the space shuttles Challenger and Columbia.
